    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-30T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-30T21:00:00-05:00" n="322"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d322">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/9104: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-31T11:00:00+09:00"
                            >July 31, 1937—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 31—12:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>238. Department’s 133, July 29, 9 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>For purposes of the record permit me to say that the integral relationship
                        between the two paragraphs in the Department’s 128, July 27, 1 p.m.,<note
                            n="27" xml:id="d322fn27">
                            <ref target="frus1937v04#pg_238">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p.
                                238</ref>.</note> was perfectly clear and in my representations to
                        the Foreign Minister on July 28th I prefaced my remarks by communicating to
                        the Minister the substance of paragraph 1. Referring to that report as to
                        Japanese intentions the Minister said “No, that is not true” and proceeded
                        to make the statement reported in paragraph 5 of my 230, July 28, 5
                            p.m.<note n="28" xml:id="d322fn28">
                            <ref target="frus1937v04#pg_239">
                                <hi rend="italic">Ibid</hi>., p. 239</ref>.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>I am in complete concurrence and sympathy with every step thus far taken
                        by the Department in connection with the present Sino-Japanese hostilities
                        and with the general policy outlined in paragraph numbered 3 of Department’s
                        133, July 29, 9 p.m.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
